The article discusses multiple classes of antipsychotics and their mechanisms of action, so there is not just one answer to this question. Each class of antipsychotics has a different mechanism of action and targets different receptors. For example, sulpiride and remoxipride block a subgroup of dopamine (DA) D2/D3 receptors, while clozapine and risperidone affect not just D2/D3 receptors but also 5HT, alpha 1, and/or D1 receptors. Partial D2 agonists, serotonin (5HT1) agonists, 5HT2 antagonists, 5HT3 antagonists, gamma-amino-butyric-acid-A (GABA-A) benzodiazepine agonists, and partial glutamate agonists are also mentioned, each with their own mechanism of action and target receptors.

Bupropion is an antidepressant that also acts as a nicotine receptor antagonist, and NRT works by delivering nicotine to the body to reduce cravings and withdrawal symptoms.
